OL,3,CSim-swap fraud rises by 1,000% as
OL,4,Ccriminals exploit two-factor
OL,5,Cauthentication
OL,7,FSim-swap fraud involves hijacking a
OL,8,Fperson's mobile phone number and
OL,9,Ftransferring it to a new sim without
OL,10,Ftheir consent.
OL,12,FOnce transferred, fraudsters can then
OL,13,Freceive texts and calls to that
OL,14,Fnumber, including important security
OL,15,Fchecks like two-factor authentication.
OL,17,FIt is one of several tactics used in
OL,18,Ftakeover fraud, where criminals take
OL,19,Fcontrol of individual accounts to
OL,20,Fdefraud their victims.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G2/16
